This paper deals with end-to-end language generation in dialogue systems, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). Specifically, the paper focuses on developing methods to generate more natural and varied outputs by characterizing the types of sentences in a large corpus of crowd-sourced data. This involves text analysis and labeling of the training data, as well as experiments with a neural generator to test the effect of different stylistic partitions and labeling methods. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language), which encompasses research on NLP and computational linguistics. The paper also involves machine learning techniques, such as neural networks, which could place it in the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper deals with generating outputs that are both semantically and stylistically controlled, which could fall under the sub-categories of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.IR (Information Retrieval). Finally, the paper involves analyzing and manipulating large datasets, which could place it in the sub-category of cs.SD (Sound).
